  ## Summary
  
  Current `org.apache.kafka:kafka-clients:4.2.0` still fails in a GraalVM native image, and the existing metadata published under `metadata/org.apache.kafka/kafka-clients/3.5.1` does not resolve it.
  
  This came from validating Micronaut Kafka issue `micronaut-projects/micronaut-kafka#1213` against the current `6.0.x` line and then checking whether the existing reachability metadata helps.
  
  Upstream issue links:
  - Micronaut Kafka issue: https://github.com/micronaut-projects/micronaut-kafka/issues/1213
  - Validation comment being followed up here: https://github.com/micronaut-projects/micronaut-kafka/issues/1213#issuecomment-4305176848
  
  ## What I verified
  
  ### 1. Old 3.9.1 failure is **not** the current 6.0.x failure
  
  The older Micronaut Kafka issue comment validated `kafka-clients:3.9.1` failing in native execution with:
  - `ClassNotFoundException: java.security.AccessController`
  - `NoSuchMethodException: javax.security.auth.Subject.current()`
  
  On the current Micronaut Kafka `6.0.x` line, the managed Kafka client version is `4.2.0`, and the current native failure is different.
  
  ### 2. Current `kafka-clients:4.2.0` failure
  
  I built a minimal Micronaut app against the current Micronaut Kafka `6.0.x` source and let it create a Kafka producer on startup with:
  - `security.protocol=SASL_PLAINTEXT`
  - `sasl.mechanism=PLAIN`
  - `sasl.jaas.config=org.apache.kafka.common.security.plain.PlainLoginModule required username="admin" password="admin-secret";`
  
  The native executable fails before any broker handshake with:
  
  ```text
  Caused by: org.apache.kafka.common.config.ConfigException: Invalid value org.apache.kafka.common.security.oauthbearer.DefaultJwtRetriever for configuration sasl.oauthbearer.jwt.retriever.class: Class org.apache.kafka.common.security.oauthbearer.DefaultJwtRetriever could not be found.
      at org.apache.kafka.common.config.ConfigDef.parseType(ConfigDef.java:789)
      at org.apache.kafka.common.config.SaslConfigs.addClientSaslSupport(SaslConfigs.java:388)
      at org.apache.kafka.clients.producer.ProducerConfig.<clinit>(ProducerConfig.java:526)
  ```
  
  ### 3. Existing metadata does not resolve it
  
  I checked the current metadata tree for `org.apache.kafka:kafka-clients` and found:
  - only `metadata/org.apache.kafka/kafka-clients/3.5.1`
  - `index.json` marks `3.5.1` as latest and lists tested versions `3.5.1` and `3.5.2`
  
  I then vendored the current `3.5.1/reachability-metadata.json` directly into the reproducer under:
  
  ```text
  src/main/resources/META-INF/native-image/org.apache.kafka/kafka-clients/reachability-metadata.json
  ```
  
  Rebuilding the native image did increase the reflected-type count, so the metadata was being consumed, but the runtime failure remained exactly the same:
  
  ```text
  Caused by: org.apache.kafka.common.config.ConfigException: Invalid value org.apache.kafka.common.security.oauthbearer.DefaultJwtRetriever for configuration sasl.oauthbearer.jwt.retriever.class: Class org.apache.kafka.common.security.oauthbearer.DefaultJwtRetriever could not be found.
  ```
  
  ## Why the current metadata appears insufficient
  
  The published `3.5.1` metadata contains entries such as:
  - `javax.security.auth.Subject`
  - `org.apache.kafka.common.security.plain.PlainLoginModule`
  - `org.apache.kafka.common.security.authenticator.DefaultLogin`
  - `org.apache.kafka.common.security.authenticator.SaslClientCallbackHandler`
  
  But it does not appear to include the OAuth bearer defaults that now fail first for `4.2.0`, such as:
  - `org.apache.kafka.common.security.oauthbearer.DefaultJwtRetriever`
  - `org.apache.kafka.common.security.oauthbearer.DefaultJwtValidator`
  
  ## Reproducer
  
  Environment used:
  - Linux aarch64
  - GraalVM CE 25.0.2
  - `native-image 25.0.2`
  
  ### App code
  
  `settings.gradle`
  ```groovy
  pluginManagement {
      repositories {
          gradlePluginPortal()
          mavenCentral()
      }
  }
  
  rootProject.name = "mkafka-1213-6x-app"
  includeBuild("/path/to/micronaut-kafka-6.0.x-worktree")
  ```
  
  `build.gradle`
  ```groovy
  plugins {
      id "io.micronaut.application" version "4.6.2"
  }
  
  repositories {
      mavenCentral()
  }
  
  dependencies {
      implementation(platform("io.micronaut.platform:micronaut-platform:4.10.11"))
      implementation("io.micronaut.kafka:micronaut-kafka")
      implementation("io.micronaut:micronaut-runtime")
      annotationProcessor("io.micronaut:micronaut-inject-java")
      runtimeOnly("org.slf4j:slf4j-simple:2.0.17")
  }
  
  application {
      mainClass = "example.Application"
  }
  
  micronaut {
      version("4.10.11")
      runtime("none")
      testRuntime("junit5")
      processing {
          incremental(true)
          annotations("example.*")
      }
  }
  ```
  
  `src/main/resources/application.properties`
  ```properties
  micronaut.application.name=mkafka-1213-6x-app
  kafka.bootstrap.servers[0]=127.0.0.1:19093
  kafka.security.protocol=SASL_PLAINTEXT
  kafka.sasl.mechanism=PLAIN
  kafka.sasl.jaas.config=org.apache.kafka.common.security.plain.PlainLoginModule required username="admin" password="admin-secret";
  ```
  
  `src/main/java/example/Application.java`
  ```java
  package example;
  
  import io.micronaut.runtime.Micronaut;
  
  public final class Application {
      private Application() {
      }
  
      public static void main(String[] args) {
          Micronaut.run(Application.class, args);
      }
  }
  ```
  
  `src/main/java/example/TasksClient.java`
  ```java
  package example;
  
  import io.micronaut.configuration.kafka.annotation.KafkaClient;
  import io.micronaut.configuration.kafka.annotation.Topic;
  
  @KafkaClient
  public interface TasksClient {
      @Topic("tasks")
      void send(String body);
  }
  ```
  
  `src/main/java/example/StartupSender.java`
  ```java
  package example;
  
  import io.micronaut.context.event.ApplicationEventListener;
  import io.micronaut.context.event.StartupEvent;
  import jakarta.inject.Singleton;
  
  @Singleton
  final class StartupSender implements ApplicationEventListener<StartupEvent> {
      private final TasksClient tasksClient;
  
      StartupSender(TasksClient tasksClient) {
          this.tasksClient = tasksClient;
      }
  
      @Override
      public void onApplicationEvent(StartupEvent event) {
          System.err.println("Sending Kafka message from startup listener");
          tasksClient.send("hello");
      }
  }
  ```
  
  ### Dummy listener
  
  A real Kafka broker is not required because the failure happens before the full broker handshake. A plain TCP listener is enough:
  
  ```sh
  perl -MIO::Socket::INET -e '$|=1; my $s=IO::Socket::INET->new(LocalAddr=>"127.0.0.1",LocalPort=>19093,Proto=>"tcp",Listen=>5,Reuse=>1) or die $!; while (my $c=$s->accept) { select(undef,undef,undef,30); close $c; }'
  ```
  
  ### Build and run without vendored metadata
  
  ```sh
  /path/to/micronaut-kafka-6.0.x-worktree/gradlew -p /tmp/mkafka-1213-6x-app nativeCompile
  timeout 20s /tmp/mkafka-1213-6x-app/build/native/nativeCompile/mkafka-1213-6x-app
  ```
  
  Observed failure:
  
  ```text
  Caused by: org.apache.kafka.common.config.ConfigException: Invalid value org.apache.kafka.common.security.oauthbearer.DefaultJwtRetriever for configuration sasl.oauthbearer.jwt.retriever.class: Class org.apache.kafka.common.security.oauthbearer.DefaultJwtRetriever could not be found.
  ```
  
  ### Build and run with the currently published metadata vendored in
  
  Add the published metadata file from:
  
  ```text
  metadata/org.apache.kafka/kafka-clients/3.5.1/reachability-metadata.json
  ```
  
  to:
  
  ```text
  src/main/resources/META-INF/native-image/org.apache.kafka/kafka-clients/reachability-metadata.json
  ```
  
  Then rebuild and rerun the same commands above.
  
  Observed result:
  - native image still builds successfully
  - runtime failure is unchanged
  - same `DefaultJwtRetriever could not be found` exception
  
  ## Requested follow-up
  
  Please add or update `org.apache.kafka:kafka-clients` metadata so that the current client line used here (`4.2.0`) is covered and the native runtime no longer fails during SASL config initialization.
  
  At minimum, this looks like it needs coverage for the OAuth bearer default classes that are now eagerly referenced during config initialization.
